      <hedline>
        <hl1>Norman Wexler's Gifts</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Freddie Gershon letter on J Hoberman's July 30 article notes screenwriter Norman Wexler's greatest commercial success was 1977's Saturday Night Fever (M)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>J. Hoberman's informative, intriguing article tells of John Avildsen, the director of ''Joe,'' and in part of the lesser-known but talented Norman Wexler, the screenwriter. Norman was a mercurial man with an uncanny ear, insight and intellect, which enabled him to succinctly encapsulate a cultural phenomenon in a 90-minute time capsule.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>J. Hoberman's informative, intriguing article tells of John Avildsen, the director of ''Joe,'' and in part of the lesser-known but talented Norman Wexler, the screenwriter. Norman was a mercurial man with an uncanny ear, insight and intellect, which enabled him to succinctly encapsulate a cultural phenomenon in a 90-minute time capsule.</p>
        <p>In 1977 he had his greatest commercial success, ''Saturday Night Fever.'' The producer, my partner, Robert Stigwood, was introduced to Norman by Mr. Avildsen. The very first draft screenplay by Norman Wexler is actually what appeared on screen. Norman's gifts were rare and are missed.</p>
        <p>FREDDIE GERSHON  Manhattan</p>
        <p>'JOE'</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
